Movement of fluid between compartments and mechanisms of edema 

Monday, May 29, 2017 

3:30 PM 

Briefly describe body water compartments and ion concentrations within these compartments 

Total body water can be divided into extracellular and intracellular. Of extracellular water, there are compartments interstitially, within lymph, and in plasma. Other forms of water storage include urine, intestinal fluid, saliva, and sweat and tears. 

 

 

For a given body weight or by percentage body weight, males hold more water than females. The lean hold more water than the obese. The young hold more water than the old.  

 

Intracellularly 

The composition of the cytosol is water + inorganic ions + organic substances.

Interestingly, there are dissolved proteins in plasma, plasma water, intracellular fluid, but not in interstitial fluid. 

 

Water and ions move from the capillary into the interstitial space, then into the cell. Ion movement is determined by diffusion and diffusion barriers (eg fully permeable, semi-permeable, and impermeable membranes). The vascular wall separating intravascular fluid in the capillary and the interstitial fluid is semi permeable. It is fully permeable to water, well-permeable for inorganic ions, glucose, and amino acids, and usually impermeable to large protein ions/molecules. 

 

The cellular membrane separating the interstitial fluid from the intracellular fluid is also semipermeable. Its permeability to specific ions is under certain control mechanisms, and are different in different tissues. In general, it is poorly permeable to inorganic ions, impermeable to most organic ions (except lipid-soluble ions) and fully permeable to water. 

 

Briefly describe and distinguish osmotic and oncotic pressure 

Hydrostatic pressure: fluid pressure from blood 

Osmotic pressure: pressure that would otherwise need to be exerted to prevent osmotic action (Conditions for osmosis include the presence of a semi-permeable membrane between two solutions, and the presence of a non-permeable solute in one solution.) 

Oncotic pressure: colloid osmotic pressure exerted by proteins, notably albumin, in a blood vessel's plasma that tends to pull water into the circulatory system 

 

Note: Osmotic pressure = Concentration of solute (Molar) x R (Ideal gas constant) x T (Kelvin) 

 

There is a balance between osmotic and hydrostatic pressure in the movement of water. Between the intracellular fluid and interstitial fluid, hydrostatic pressure is the same and osmotic pressure may vary. Between the plasma and interstitial fluid, both hydrostatic and osmotic pressures may vary. 

 

 

Briefly describe the action of oncotic and hydrostatic pressures (Starling's forces) acting on fluid movement out of and into the capillary 

Fluid moves out of then back into the capillary due to the interaction between hydrostatic and oncotic pressures. Hydrostatic pressure steadily drops across the capillary, from the arterial end (35mmHg) to the venal end (10mmHg). However, the oncotic pressure stays the same throughout at around 25mmHg. Hence, water moves out of the capillary initially due to hydrostatic pressure, then back in due to oncotic pressure.  

 

Note: The capillary contains pores that allow the free passage of water, small organic ions, glucose, and amino acids, but not large protein molecules. Hence, concentrations of inorganic ions in plasma and interstitial fluid are similar, but there are much higher protein levels in the capillary. This results in a constant oncotic pressure along the capillary.  

 

Fluid movement between the interstitial fluid and intracellular fluid is driven by ion gradients, produced by ion pumps.  

 

Briefly describe the role of lymphatic drainage in removal of accumulated fluid from the interstitial space 

Lymphatic capillaries collect excess interstitial fluid and carry them back through lymph vessels into the systemic circulation. This occurs through one-way valves, the contraction of smooth muscle in the wall of lymphatic vessels, and the compression of lymphatic vessels by skeletal muscle contraction. Lymphatic vessels are most abundant in the GI, liver, skin and lungs. When capillaries are damaged, proteins will leak into the interstitial fluid and be cleared by the lymph vessels. Lipoproteins are also in the interstitial fluid. 

 

The functions of lymph are: 

-Return of protein and fluid from interstitial space to maintain the oncotic pressure gradient and prevent edema 

-Role in absorption and transport of fat from the small intestine 

-Immunological role with lymph glands and circulation of immune cells such as lymphocytes 

 

Describe the mechanisms of edema including venous obstruction, lymphatic obstruction, lowered oncotic pressure, increased capillary permeability 

Edema is the accumulation of fluid in the interstitial space due to elevated intra-capillary pressure (eg elevated venous pressure from an obstruction, preventing outflow of water from interstitial space), reduced plasma oncotic pressure (eg renal loss of plasma proteins, reduced liver production of proteins), and blocked lymphatic ducts. Increased capillary permeability due to proinflammatory mediators or structural damage results in the leakage of fluid from the capillaries into the interstitial space.  

 

Briefly describe the consequences of pulmonary edema (interstitial and alveolar) on lung compliance and gas exchange 

Lung compliance: decreased change in volume over change in pressure, hence decreased lung compliance 

Gas exchange: reduced gas exchange due to reduced surface area of alveoli
